.TH "tipc_getname" 9 "tipc_getname" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
tipc_getname \- get port ID of socket or peer socket
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" tipc_getname
.BI "(struct socket *sock "  ","
.BI "struct sockaddr *uaddr "  ","
.BI "int peer "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "sock" 12
socket structure
.IP "uaddr" 12
area for returned socket address
.IP "peer" 12
0 = own ID, 1 = current peer ID, 2 = current/former peer ID
.SH "RETURN"
0 on success, errno otherwise
.SH "NOTE"
This routine doesn't need to take the socket lock since it only
accesses socket information that is unchanging (or which changes in
a completely predictable manner).
